708441f-a.text:
Fifth Avenue, east side, north from and including 26th Street, showing the N.W. corner of Msdison Square and the Hotel Brunswiclt on the N.E. corner of 20th Street. According to King's Handbook of New York (1892), parades of the Coaching Club always started in front of the Brunswick, and he mentions it as much favored by English tourists. This photograph was taken by one such Englishman, and was annotated in his own writing "Where I stayed with
Lucas C. E. en route from Venezuela to England".
About 1906 this building will be replaced by the 12-story Brunswick Building, as Madison Square changes into a strictly business district.
1888.

711833f-a.text:
26th Street east from Fifth Avenue, taken from roof of the Cafe Martin. This picture gives a good view of Madison Square Garden (1889-1925), and the lovely Diana of St. Gaudens, poised atop its tower. The Garden was acquired by the New York Life Insurance Company in 1915 at a foreclosure sale, and in 1920 was saved from demolition by Tex Rickard, who signed a ten year lease on it. In 1924 the New York LLife bought back this 1ease and in 1925 tore down the Garden,to build their present edifice on its site. Diana, however, is still to be seen in Fairmont
Tark, Philadelphia.
In the centre, with the Uneeda Biscuit sign on its roof, is the Hotel Brunswick, and at the extreme left is the Hotel Victoria, made famous by the patronage of President Cleveland. To the right of the Garden is the former Jerome residence, later the University
Club and now (1935) the Manhattan Club.
About 1898.
Browning Studios.
